Peanut Butter Blossoms
One batch makes about 24 cookies

Preheat oven to 375F

INGREDIENTS:
* 1-¾ cups all purpose flour
* 1 teaspoon baking soda
* ½ teaspoon table salt
* ½ cup unsalted butter, room temperature
* ½ cup granulated sugar
* ½ cup light brown sugar , lightly-packed
* ¾ cup smooth peanut butter (not “natural” peanut butter)
* 1 teaspoon vanilla extract
* 1 large egg
* 40 Hershey Kisses 

INSTRUCTIONS:
* In a bowl, whisk together flour, baking soda, and salt. Set aside.
* In the bowl of a stand mixer fitted with the paddle attachment, or a large bowl with an electric hand mixer, beat butter until smooth. Cream the butter, ½ cup granulated sugar, light brown sugar and peanut butter until light and fluffy. 
* Scrape the bottom and sides of the mixing bowl. Beat in vanilla and the egg, until combined.
* Add the flour mixture and mix until a stiff dough forms. 
* Scoop the dough into 1-¼ inch portions (40-42 portions), you can roll them into balls if desired. Place on ungreased baking sheets, 2 inches apart.
* Bake the cookies 8-10 minutes, until set, lightly brown, and just starting to crack.
* As soon as you remove the cookies from the oven, gently press a Hershey’s kiss into each center. (The cookies will crack – this is normal). After about 5 minutes, transfer the cookies to a wire rack to cool completely, at least an hour. (The chocolate should be firm before the cookies are stored.)
* Store at room temperature in an airtight container for 3-5 days, or freeze for 2-3 months.

Start with what you have and build on it. 

Follow these tips to kickstart your pantry makeover:

2. Smart Shopping: Gradually build your pantry by picking up a few extra items on each grocery run. Look for versatile ingredients that can be used in multiple dishes.
3. Organize: This not only keeps things tidy but also helps you see what you have at a glance.

🫙Elevate Your Pantry Game with Pressure Canning! 🫙

Let’s talk about why pressure canning is a game-changer for food preservation.

Benefit 1: Lock in Freshness! Pressure canning seals in nutrients and flavors keeping your food as fresh as the day you canned it.

Benefit 2: Shelf Stability! Say goodbye to freezer burn - pressure canned food stays fresh for years, meaning you’ll always have a stocked pantry.

Benefit 3: Versatile Preservation! From garden veggies to homemade soups, pressure canning lets you preserve a wide variety of foods.

Benefit 4: DIY Convenience! No more last-minute grocery runs - have your favorite meals ready to heat and eat in minutes.

Ok let’s talk about it! Almost a year ago, creators like myself were being asked to try out (and yes, promote) a vacuum sealer that was for mason jars.

Now - it’s a nice product FOR DOING WHAT IT IS MADE TO DO - which is extending the shelf life of DRY goods like flour, beans, rice etc. etc.

What it is NOT - is a replacement for proper water bath and pressure canning techniques. Sealed jars DO NOT equal safe jars.

Unfortunately, I’m still getting well-intended people telling me how they “canned food” with this thing. No - no you did not. You’re going to make yourself sick!

Please do your research before doing any sort of food preservation project.

After you have put the weighted gauge on - the pressure inside of the All American 921 pressure canner will build.
Once it reaches pressure - the gauge will start to jiggle. 

The gauge NEEDS to jiggle at a minimum of 3 times a minute - ideally 3 to 4 tomes a minute.

NOTE: The heat settings will vary from stovetop to stovetop. So use what works for you, but the general principles still apply.
